text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%0a!Morphosynatic Diversity of the Perfective 'Done'%0a%0a:Author: jess_smith%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aA summary of the grammatical construction of 'done', what dialects use it this way, and more.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn African American English, or AAE, and some southern dialects, the 'perfective' done is used in multiple different scenarios. The main use of 'done' is to signify a completed past even, like "I done already ate there' or 'He done that chore yesterday' (Note, the combination of the perfective 'done' with the time adverbs suggest that the action has already been completed in the past). The perfective 'done' can be done in many more ways though, usually with event-related, or eventive, verbs (I done called you). It can also be used with negation like 'didn't' (I didn't done that yet). Overall, perfective done is used in 4 main ways, like the perfect result (similar to recent past, an event that just occurred but may still be occuring), existential perfect (an event or thought that occurred at least once), recent past (a recently concluded event), and universal perfect (an event or condition that has continued for a long period).%0a%0aA good distinction between the southern perfective done and the AAE perfective done is that the southern perfective done also use it after 'to-be' verbs, while this does not traditionally happen in the AAE dialect (I'm done tired now).%0a%0aReferences:%0ahttps://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/perfective-done#who-says-this%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210329-180127-827160#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Perfective Done Historically Seen as Marker of Class %0a-> - AlexisA%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI found this really interesting, so I did some extra research (primarily at https://books.google.com/books?id=OqUBUgW_Ax8C&pg=PA287&lpg=PA287&dq=perfective+done&source=bl&ots=wbTjJ79RdP&sig=ACfU3U3I14iqazzKpvrU1J82-vHEnvNDXQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiOzumpiNbvAhUQVd8KHfEVDVQQ6AEwDHoECBgQAw#v=onepage&q=perfective%2520done&f=false - page 287-288) and found that at least one scholar considered the perfective done to be a mark of the working class as recently as the late 1970s. In a small study, they found the construction to be used by around 2/3 of working class individuals in the south (leaving implicit that it was less common among other classes). I imagine this is largely due to the structure of neighborhoods in the United States and elsewhere, where most people live in the same neighborhoods (and, consequently, go to the same schools, grocery stores, etc) as others of a similar class. I wonder if this indicates that environmental influences are more powerful in shaping a person's dialect than cultural ones (ie television, books, etc) since people in a variety of communities tend to watch many of the same shows, read some of the same books, etc but still have substantially different dialects.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210329-180127-827160#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)
